# Package Installation Guidelines

## Package Manager
- Use `pnpm` for all package management
- Don't install packages in the root directory
- Always install packages in the `apps/web` directory

## Installation Commands

### Installing Dependencies
```sh
cd apps/web
pnpm add package-name
```

### Installing Dev Dependencies
```sh
cd apps/web
pnpm add -D package-name
```

### Installing Global Packages
```sh
pnpm add -g package-name
```

## AstroMatch Specific Examples

### Installing React Dependencies
```sh
cd apps/web
pnpm add react react-dom
```

### Installing UI Libraries
```sh
cd apps/web
pnpm add @radix-ui/react-dialog @radix-ui/react-dropdown-menu
```

### Installing Development Tools
```sh
cd apps/web
pnpm add -D @types/node @types/react @types/react-dom
```

### Installing Supabase
```sh
cd apps/web
pnpm add @supabase/supabase-js
```

### Installing SWR for Data Fetching
```sh
cd apps/web
pnpm add swr
```

### Installing Form Libraries
```sh
cd apps/web
pnpm add react-hook-form @hookform/resolvers zod
```

## Why Use pnpm?
- **Faster**: pnpm is significantly faster than npm
- **Disk Efficient**: Uses hard links to avoid duplicating packages
- **Strict**: Prevents phantom dependencies
- **Monorepo Friendly**: Better support for monorepo structures

## Directory Structure
```
AstroMatch1/
├── apps/
│   └── web/           # Install packages here
│       ├── package.json
│       ├── node_modules/
│       └── ...
├── package.json       # Root package.json (don't install here)
└── ...
```

## Best Practices
- Always run `cd apps/web` before installing packages
- Use `pnpm` instead of `npm` or `yarn`
- Keep root `package.json` minimal
- Install all project dependencies in `apps/web`
- Use `pnpm add -D` for development dependencies
- Use `pnpm add` for production dependencies
